Chesster

Chess Solitaire

**Product Description**

We will make a chess bot that takes a user's games as input data and learns their playstyle. This will allow the user to play against an opponent that mimics their playstyle. Our bot will make moves that the user most commonly makes in each game state/position. For game states without existing moves, our bot will extrapolate the most probable move based on similar plays and game states.

To implement this bot and provide the aforementioned features, the user must upload previous game data including game state and plays to our server. We will sequentially process this data using a custom-built chess data preprocessor. Then, the data will be uploaded to a machine learning model and trained to output the most probable chess move played by the user at a given game state.

Our product allows users to compete against themselves, find flaws in their playstyles, and evaluate different playstyles that their existing playstyles fail against.

**Major Features**

- Take data in chess algebraic notation and convert to board states. Represent the actual state of the board and label with the move taken.
- Save board states for each user in a database on the backend so that each bot can be trained on a dataset unique to each user.
- Train chess bot for each user with the data saved so that it can replicate the style of play the user has.
- Allow user to play against a personalized bot online through a GUI

**Stretch Goals**

- Link to an existing chess platform (lichess) so the user doesn't have to upload data manually
- Save games each user plays against our chess bots for future training (i.e. iterative updating of the bot)

# Non-functional Requirements

- **Scalability & Efficiency:** We should have a scalable pipeline for training the bots for each user. Training the neural network will be a significant part of the computation investment. Having a fast, scalable method for creating the customized bot would help lower this investment.
- **User convenience:** We would like to have a user interface that is graphical and modern, with the same clean and professional as modern chess platforms, including but not limited to the ability to premove, view legal moves, and flip the board.
- **Accessibility:** We want to make our product accessible to as many people as possible. We will do this using different accessibility-focused techniques including but not limited to using colorblind friendly colors for our UI and using large fonts.
- **Privacy:** We want to follow the strictest privacy guidelines so that user game data remains secure and only visible by the user themselves.
- **Accuracy**: Given adequate data, we expect to achieve an accuracy of 70%, i.e. the bot mimics the user's playing style at least 70% of the time (to be evaluated).

# External Requirements

- **Robustness:** Our platform should provide for all possible error states and handle these gracefully. The behavior should be clearly defined. For example, users won't be allowed to make invalid moves and stalemates shouldn't cause the program to crash.
- **Accessible / Installable**: Our platform should support different web browsers (Safari, Chrome, Edge, etc.) and be accessible to the public through an URL.
- **Reproducible**: The README.md will contain detailed instructions on how to build our service from source and set up their own server. We will follow the industry-approved guidelines for documenting our work even though the focus would be on delivering the product as per Agile principles.
- **Scope**: We believe that the scope of this project matches the size of the team (6 people). While it might seem that there are a relatively small number of tasks, each of these tasks (data processing, model training) are very complex and each come with their own set of caveats and edge cases that need to be considered. If at any time we believe that this scope-team fit no longer exists, we will work with the course staff to redefine / restructure the project.

#

**Test Plan & Bugs:**

We will need to test our system in three parts: the UI/UX, data pipeline, and ML pipeline.

Unit testing: We will collaborate to determine all the test cases we need for each part of our system, then write the test cases before writing the code.

Usability testing: We will find volunteer participants to test our project before each release (Beta, Gamma, and Final). We will use their feedback to determine how to improve our UI and where the bot succeeds/falls short.

System testing: We will use GitHub actions to run automated system integration tests.

**Documentation Plan:**

As we plan features, we will add them to documents for users, and potential server hosters who want to either use our product, or to host it themselves. These files will all be included in the github.

We will use our architecture diagrams to inform our design decisions. Comprehensive comments will be required for all non-trivial code, keeping in mind the Agile philosophy of focusing on "why" comments rather than "what" comments.

**Need for External Feedback**

As a customer-obsessed team, we will seek customer feedback at every stage of our development process. This may involve having meetings with chess-playing friends when they can try out our product and give suggestions. However, the specific stage where external feedback is most needed is immediately after the core infrastructure has been developed but before launch. We envision sharing our completed product with our personal networks for a "beta release" as an additional layer of user testing before we open up access to the entire world. Participants in our beta release will be asked to fill out a form where they rate Chesster and provide us with both aspects of the product they liked and aspects they think we can improve upon.

### Major Software Components

The major software components we plan to use are separated into 3 parts. ML, data, and UI/UX. The ML group will be responsible for the agent and training sections, which will be responsible for the pipeline of creating an evaluation model for states that will favor the playstyle of a user. They will also write the code surrounding the evaluation model to turn it into an agent that can interact with the game. To send to UI/UX and vice versa. The data group will be responsible for the entire data pipeline and all data preprocessing. They will be responsible for taking in the PGN files from users and turning them into usable data for ML. They will not interact with ML directly, but only with UI/UX and the database. UI/UX will be responsible for the frontend of the project, making the website which can interface with the user they will provide the game states and the signal to train a model for the ML group, as well as the raw data for the data pipeline.

The interfaces between components will be the ML team will interface with data through the database directly. UI/UX will interface with ML through API calls. It will also deliver the data to the data pipeline through API calls.

The data schema we will use will be in mongoDB. We will use 2 collections, one for storing the data of a user, and one for storing the models under a user, as well as any additional information around the user.

game_data

One decision we made in the software architecture was to store the games in the database directly instead of the text data. We decided to do this because it would make the architecture easier to manage, and we can more easily parse the data and remove bad data. This should also make the task of the ML group easier, as the data can be grabbed directly from the database and used without additional processing. The cons of this are that the text data is far more compact, and easy to store, it will also take up less space.

A second decision we made in the software architecture was to make the model an evaluation network and not a policy network directly. The reason we decided to do this was because we believed this would be an easy way to manage the models, and easier to train. One potential downside of this is that we have to have a separate bit of code to take the evaluations and actually use that to return an action.

# Software Design

**UI/UX Component (React + TypeScript)**

- AuthenticationModule: Manages login/registration and JWT token storage
- ChessGameInterface: Renders board (React-chessboard), validates moves (Chess.js), displays legal moves as grey circles
- FileUploadModule: Handles manual PGN upload or OAuth integration with Chess.com/Lichess APIs
- TrainingModule: Sends training requests via POST /api/train-model, polls for progress updates, displays progress bar
- AgentInterface: Sends game state (FEN) to backend via POST /api/get-move, receives move (SAN notation), updates board

**Data Pipeline Component (Python + Flask/FastAPI)**

- APIHandler: Exposes POST /api/upload-pgn endpoint for receiving PGN files
- PGNDownloader: Retrieves game history from chess platform APIs with pagination and rate limiting
- PGNParser: Converts PGN text to structured games using python-chess, extracts metadata (ELO, time control, results)
- GameValidator: Filters low-quality games (ELO < 1000, incomplete games, fast time controls)
- MoveExtractor: Traverses games to extract board states (FEN) and corresponding moves (SAN)
- StateSerializer: Structures data as {fen, move_made, move_number} tuples
- DatabaseManager: Bulk inserts into MongoDB with compound indexes on (user_id, game_id)

**ML Training Component (Python + PyTorch)**

- TrainingOrchestrator: Receives training requests, validates data sufficiency (min 10 games, 500 positions), queues jobs
- MongoDataLoader: Retrieves game states, splits into 80% training / 20% validation
- StateEncoder: Converts FEN to 12×8×8 tensors (12 piece-type channels, 8×8 board) plus castling/en passant/turn channels
- EvaluationNetwork: ResNet-style CNN with 10-20 residual blocks, outputs evaluation score \[-1, 1\]
- Trainer: Runs 50 epochs with Adam optimizer, loss based on move frequencies
- ModelCheckpointer: Saves models to GridFS (if > 16MB) or models collection
- MetadataLogger: Records training date, validation accuracy, hyperparameters, version number

**ML Agent Component (Python + PyTorch)**

- AgentAPIHandler: Receives FEN via POST /api/get-move, returns SAN move
- ModelLoader: Queries models collection for active model, downloads from GridFS if needed
- ModelCache: LRU cache of 10 models in memory to avoid repeated database loads
- PolicyGenerator: Minimax search with alpha-beta pruning to depth 3-5
- EvaluationFunction: Wraps neural network to score positions during search
- LegalMoveGenerator: Uses python-chess to generate all legal moves
- SearchAlgorithm: Alpha-beta pruning to reduce search space
- MoveSelector: Chooses highest-scoring move, breaks ties randomly

**Database Component (MongoDB 6.0+)**

- game_data collection: Stores {user_id, games\[{game_id, metadata, states\[{fen, move_made, move_number}\]}\]}  
    Indexed on user_id and (user_id, game_id)
- models collection: Stores {user_id, model_id, model_file_id (GridFS ref), metadata, is_active}  
    Indexed on user_id and (user_id, is_active)
- users collection: Stores {user_id, username, email, password_hash, created_at, last_login}  
    Unique indexes on user_id, username, email
- GridFS: Splits models > 16MB into 255KB chunks across fs.files (metadata) and fs.chunks (binary data)

**Access patterns:**

Data Pipeline: Bulk inserts

ML Training: Large reads for training data, single model upload

ML Agent: Relies on cache, infrequent DB reads on cache miss

# Coding Guidelines

**TypeScript Style Guide:** <https://google.github.io/styleguide/tsguide.html>

We decided to use Google's Style Guide for TypeScript because TypeScript does not have an official style guide on their website other than a [short list of do's and don'ts](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/declaration-files/do-s-and-don-ts.html). Google's version is more robust and will lead to fewer style conflicts in the long run. Additionally, Google is a reputable company and has free, public tools to enforce their style guide. [We can use their GTS tool](https://github.com/google/gts) to ensure that we stick to the style guide. GTS is a formatter, linter, and automatic code fixer.

**Python Style Guide:** <https://google.github.io/styleguide/pyguide.html>

We are also using Google's Style Guide for Python. An official Python style guide also exists, but this option allows us to stay consistent with our decision to use Google's guide for TypeScript. To ensure we stick to the style guide, we will use Google's recommended tools: [Black](https://github.com/psf/black) (auto-formatter) and pylint (linter) with the linter file provided in the style guide.
